-- Spanish Stocks: BBVA, Santander, Cepsa, La Seda, Solaria Move
-- B y   P a u l   T o b i n   a n d   M a n u e l   B a i g o r r i
-- 2010-11-19T16:51:54Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-18/acs-elecnor-ferrovial-iberian-stock-preview-for-nov-19.html
Spain’s  IBEX 35 Index  fell for the
first time in three days, slipping 53.6, or 0.5 percent, to
10,271.7 at the close in Madrid. The measure has advanced 0.4
percent this week.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
Spanish market. Symbols are in parentheses after company names.  Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria SA  (BBVA SM) fell 1 percent
to 8.26 euros, the second drop this week. Spain’s second-largest
bank today ends a 5.06 billion-euro ($6.9 billion) rights
offering.  Banco de Sabadell SA  (SAB SM) fell 3.1 percent to 3.23
euros, erasing the last two days of gains.  Banco Santander SA 
(SAN SM) dropped 1.8 percent to 8.53 euros.  Banco Popular
Espanol SA  (POP SM) slid 1.4 percent to 4.23 euros.  Banks fell across Europe as European Union, International
Monetary Fund and European Central Bank officials spent a second
day in Dublin discussing a possible bailout of Ireland’s banks.  Ferrovial SA  (FER SM) climbed 1.6 percent to 7.89 euros,
the stock’s third gain this week. The U.K. competition regulator
said it may reconsider its ruling that Ferrovial’s BAA Ltd. unit
must sell three airports after the U.K. government cancel plans
to build a third runway at Heathrow.  Separately, Ferrovial closed the sale of its 10 percent
stake in the 407 Express Toll Route near Toronto to Canada
Pension Plan Investment Board, the company said in a regulatory
filing.  La Seda de Barcelona SA  (SED SM) added 1.7 percent to 6
euro cents, extending yesterday’s 1.7 percent gain. La Seda said
its planned sale of a plant in San Roque to  Compania Espanola de
Petroleos SA  (CEP SM) will have a positive impact of 4 million
euros. Cepsa advanced 0.4 percent to 18.70 euros.  Solaria Energia y Medio Ambiente SA  (SLR SM) slipped 1.6
percent to 1.52 euros, extending yesterday’s 1.3 percent drop.
The Spanish government slashed subsidies paid to new solar-power
projects to limit the cost of electricity for homes and
businesses. Spain reduced the subsidized price to be earned by
ground-based photovoltaic plants by 45 percent in a Royal
Decree, the Industry Ministry said today in an e-mailed
statement. Solar-panel installations on residential roofs will
be paid 5 percent less.  To contact the reporters on this story:
